14973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114973"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of increasing shortness of breath, dry cough, night sweats and feeling hot and sweaty. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He has no known allergies. There is no history of exposure to soils or potting mix, air conditioning systems, or recent travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 92/min, blood pressure 135/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.4\u00b0C. Physical examination of the chest is unremarkable. Investigations reveal normal full blood count, electrolytes, urea and creatinine, liver function tests, and venous blood gas. His C-reactive protein is 31 mg/L (\u0026lt;10). Chest X-ray shows slight patchy opacity in the left perihilar region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is this patient\u0027s SMART-COP score?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0","1","2","3","5"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe SMART-COP score is a validated tool used to assess the severity of community-acquired pneumonia and predict the need for intensive respiratory or vasopressor support (IRVS). It was developed in Australia and has been widely adopted for risk stratification of patients with pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient scores \u003Cstrong\u003E3\u003C/strong\u003E points on the SMART-COP scale, calculated as follows: respiratory rate \u226525/min (1 point) and oxygen saturation \u0026lt;93% in a patient aged \u0026lt;50 years (2 points). The patient does not score points for the other criteria: systolic blood pressure is \u0026gt;90 mmHg, there is no multilobar involvement on chest X-ray, albumin was not measured but is likely normal given normal liver function tests, heart rate is \u0026lt;125/min, there is no confusion mentioned, and pH was not measured but is likely normal given normal venous blood gas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA score of \u003Cstrong\u003E0\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate no risk factors present, which is incorrect as this patient has tachypnoea and hypoxaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA score of \u003Cstrong\u003E1\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003E2\u003C/strong\u003E would underestimate the severity by not accounting for both the respiratory rate and oxygen saturation abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA score of \u003Cstrong\u003E5\u003C/strong\u003E would require additional abnormalities not present in this patient, such as hypotension, multilobar involvement, or acidaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith a SMART-COP score of 3, this patient has moderate severity pneumonia with approximately a 1 in 8 risk of requiring IRVS. This would typically warrant hospital admission with close monitoring and consideration of broad-spectrum antibiotics covering both typical and atypical pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SMART-COP score helps predict the need for intensive respiratory or vasopressor support in community-acquired pneumonia."],"references":["Charles PG, Wolfe R, Whitby M, Fine MJ, Fuller AJ, Stirling R, et al. SMART-COP: a tool for predicting the need for intensive respiratory or vasopressor support in community-acquired pneumonia. Clin Infect Dis. 2008;47(3):375-84."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96979"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1406"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96979"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T17:52:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T17:53:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1406"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questi